# Medial Collateral Ligament (Elbow UCL)

> The **medial collateral ligament** (MCL) of the elbow — also called the **ulnar collateral ligament (UCL)** — is the primary stabilizer against valgus stress at the elbow, connecting the [[Medial Epicondyle]] of the [[Humerus]] to the [[Ulna]].

## 🔗 Key Connections
- **Origin** — [[Medial Epicondyle]] of [[Humerus]]
- **Insertion** — Medial [[Ulna]] (sublime tubercle of coronoid process)
- **Three bundles** — Anterior (strongest), posterior, transverse

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Tommy John surgery (UCL reconstruction)** — UCL rupture in overhead throwing athletes (baseball pitchers); reconstructed with palmaris longus or gracilis tendon graft
- **Valgus stress test** — Tests UCL integrity; medial elbow pain/gapping
- **Medial elbow pain** — UCL sprain/tear from repetitive valgus load in throwing athletes

## 📍 Location
[[Skeletal System]] → Upper Limb → [[Humerus]] → [[Medial Epicondyle]] → Medial Collateral Ligament
